{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930063001/0318.xml":{"full_text":"20\na _____ 1,11\nFuture Trend of Stocks Depends Upon Commodity News, Soys Spectator\nlEFIECMI HF BULLISH\nmen is seei\nStatement by Patrick E. Crowley Declared\nAid for Stocks on Their Upward Swing;\nShort Interests Active, However\n_____ S ________\nBy THE SPECTATOR\nI look for further temporary rallying tendencies hi the stock\nmarket today. The statement of Patrick E. Crowley, presi\ndent of the New York Central Lines, after Saturday\u2019s close,\nthat business has definitely turned the corner, should exert a\nbullish effect, for the time being. His statement follows other\noptimistic expression by several industrial leaders, and such\nindications of confidence in the business outlook are likely to\nhave their effect before long. On the other hand, publication\nof further unfavorable earnings statements by leading railroad\nand industrial corporations would exert a bearish influence,\nand the short sellers wpuld not hesitate to take advantage of\ntheir opportunity. Therefore, it is a toss-up as to which way\nthe market may turn. I expect the opening to be firm to\nstrong. The course of the market throughout the rest of the\nsession will depend on new developments, chiefly from com\nmodity markets.\nDullness Ahead\nAt the end of Saturday\u2019s record\ndull session, in which only 587,590\nshares were traded in, most brok\ners and leading operators were\ninclined to believe that the long-\ndull summer period\nhad arrived and that commission\nhouses would do little business\nuntil the first of September. It\nwas the quietest Saturday since\nJdly, 1928.\nBendix Aviation should do bet\nter in view of the report that\nthe company probably will earn\nits second quarter dividend in the\nface of general depression in the\nautomotive and aircraft indus\ntries.\nWeakness in Timken\nThe bears devoted plenty of at\nteniotn to Timken Roller Bearing\nSaturday, hammering it down to\na new low at 57% on expectation\nof poor business during the sum\nmer months. Before the autumn\ncollapse, Timken seemed to be in\nexcellent position, with its de\nmand from both automobile and\nrailway sources, but the business\ndepression has resulted -in esti\nmated tft|it dwningr tor this year\nwill be only slightly, more than\n88 a share, compared with 88.19\na share last year;\nJohns-Manville registered a new\n1930 low Saturday. If there is\nno pickup in residential building\nsoon, this issue is likely to estab\nlish a lower bottom.\nStore Sales Increase\nFor the last three business\ndays, we have been hearing more\ncheerful news than has come in\nfor several months. The latest\nimportant development in this\ndirection is the announcement\nthat in the first five months of\n1030, sales of mail order and\nchain stores gained about 5.38\nper cent over sales of the first\nfive .months of 1929, the most\nprosperous year of all times. A\n2 per cent decrease was recorded\nin March, but substantial gains\nwere experienced in each of the\nother four months. May sales\nwere 4.1 per cent larger than\nthose of May. 1929.\nExpansion of store chains is\nlargely responsible tor the gains,\nalthough old established stores,\n\u25a0N STEEL\nDIV. GUT TO SI\nDirectors of the 'Sharon Steel\nHoop Company, today halved the\ndividend by declaring a quarterly\ndividend of 25 cents a share on\nthe common stock placing the\nIssue on a 81 annual basis\nagainst the 82 previously paid.\nThe dividend is payable July 25\nto holders of record July 5\nDirectors of the company de\nclared that the company is in a\nstoring financial condition and\nhas In the treasury large amounts\noff cash and securities bought in\nthe open market during the last\nfew months.\nPittsburgh Steel\nDirectors of the Pittsburgh\nSteel Foundry Company today\ndeclared the usual extra dividend\nof 25 cents a share in addition to\nthe regular quarterly dividend of\n25 cents payable July 15 to hold\ners of record July 7.\nIndiana Pipe\nIndiana Pipe tine Company to\nday declared the usual extra divi\ndend Os 25 cents a share in ad\ndition to the regular quarterly\ndividend of 50 cents payable\nAugust 15 to holders of record\nJuly 25.\nWestern Pacific\nWestern Pacific Railroad Com\npany had net an operating deficit\nfor May of 8179,120 against a net\nincome of 882.705 in May. 1929.\nFor the five months ended May\n31 there was a net operating de\nfldt of $579,898\u2019 against a sur\nplus of 8825,505 in the corre\nsponding 1929 period.\nWASHINGTON TIMES- FINAHCIAL NEWS\nlacking such expansion, also have\nreported fair increase of sales.\nLifting of pressure on General\nElectric and Westinghouse is due\nto belief among professional\nspeculators that these issues have\nbeen thoroughly liquidated.\nVanadium\u2019s Market Action\nOn every rally in the market,\nVanadium moves ahead briskly,\nand the shorts fall over each\nother in their stampede to cover.\nNo doubt, there is a large short\ninterest in the stock, which had\na sensational rise to 143% before\nthe liquidation began a few\nweeks ago. Now. with the stock\ndown to 78% it is practically im\npossible to borrow 100 shares of\nthe stock, which tends to dis\ncourage the most courageous\nshort seller. And sustained rally\nis likely to bring a sharp rise in\nthis issue, and I have no hesi\ntancy in recommending its pur\nchase under 80.\nSponsors of Electric Power and\nLight have been giving the stock\nexcellent support on declines, and\naccumulating it on rallies. Its\ngain of 7 points Saturday was a\nfair indication of the good buy\ning and the nervousness of the\nshorts.\nAmerican Can Prospects\nWhen a sustained recovery\ncomes into the market, it is a\nsafe bet that American Can will\nbe one of the most prominent\nleaders. It is difficult to ac\ncount for the decline of this\nissue from its 1930 high of 156\nto its low of 108. It closed Sat\nurday at 114%, a fractional gain\non the day. There are few com\npanies in any industries that\nhave better prospects for this\nyear than American Can. As I\nhave stated before, the fruit and\nvegetable growers of the Pacific\nCoast \u2018are practically certain to\nhave on the best years in his\ntory. There will be an enormous\ndemand for metal containers, and\nthe chief benefit of this demand\nwill accrue to American Can and\nContinental Can. the two really\nimportant companies in this field.\nIt is likely that American Can\u2019s\nearnings for 1930 will approxi\nmate closely its profits of last\nyear. A veteran trader remarked\nlast week that anyone who sells\nCan short around present prices\nhas more nerve than brains. And\nI agree.\nAPPROPRIATION\nPEAK IS SEEN\u2019\nWith appropriations for the\npresent session already at a new\npeacetime peak, the day for the\nlong-predicted \u201cFive Billion Dollar\nCongress\u201d is near at hand.\nCongress has thus far appro\npriated $4,824,445,470 in the pres\nent session, according to records\nof the House Appropriations Com\nmittee, including two bills not\nfinally agreed upon. This com\npares with $4,665,000,000 last\nyear.\nThe steady growth in Federal\ngovernmental expenditures has\nbrought forth economy warnings\nfrom President Hoover and some\nCongressional leaders.\nExpendlutres rose steadily even\nduring the Coolidge economy\nregime, and they are expected to\ngrow in the future. Not only\ndoes the natural growth of the\ncountry increase Federal necessi\nties, but big authorizations of the\npresent session for soldiers' pen\nsions and rivers and harbors\ncreate new liabilities.\nThe mounting cost of Federal\nexpenditures is shown in the Ap\npropriation Committee\u2019s table for\nthe last five years:\n1926 $4,151,682,049\n1927 4,409,463,389\n1928 4,211,011.352\n1926 4.633.577,973\n1930 4,665.236.678\nThe only decrease in Federal\nexpenditures in the last decade\nwas in 1925, when they were cut\n$250,000,000 from the previous\nyear, with war lightening.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nOptimist\n\u2014Photo by Underwood\nPATRICK E. CROWLEY\nPRESIDENT OF the New\nYork Central Railroad, whose\nassertion that business has\n\u201cturned the comer\u201d made in a\nspeech recently, has caused\nmuch comment in financial\ncircles. It is believed his\nstatement will have some effect\nin speeding the recovery of\nbusiness.\nmH\nIN BUSINESS\nThe week, which practically\nclosed a half-year of readjust\nment, developed nothing funda\nmentally new in the commercial\nand financial situation, R. D.\nDun Co. states today in its\nweekly trade review. Movements\nof the same general char\nacter as those which long since\nbecame familiar, and experienced\nobservers do not. look for changes\nof deep significance at this sea\nson.\nSome gains continue to be made\nin certain quarters, and there\neven are instances of conspicuous\nactivity, but such phases remain\nthe decided exception and are\nlargely obscured in a broad sur\nvey of conditions. One of the\nchief points of strength is the\nfact that corrections of unwhole\nsome elements are taking place,\nand among the most important of\nthese is the bringing about of an\nimproved status in supplies.\nCurtailment Necessary\nWith a different basis of de\nmand existing now, production of\nlast year's rate obviously could\nnot he. .sustained, retrenchment\nin manufacture being essential to\nthe working off of accumulated\nstocks of goods. Hence, curtail\nment of outputs, although al\nways temporarily unsettling when\nof extensive scope, is a necessary\npart of the present pegjod of re\nhabilitation and recovery.\nThrough that action, a more\nsolid foundation should be laid,\nwith an ultimate check to the\nprotracted decline in commodity\nprices. The latter trend has as\nyet shown no signs of ending,\nDun\u2019s list of wholesale quotations\nagainst disclosing a large prepon\nderance of reductions.\nNo Real Breakdown\nActual or prospective unfavor\nable earnings reports and dividend\ndeclarations have served to\nsharply depress prices for secur\nities, but there has been none of\nthe speculative disorder that ac\ncompanied last Autumn\u2019s break\ndown. After six months of 1930,\nvigorous trade revival is yet to\nbe witnessed, the unusual ram\nifications of economic transition\nhaving cuased a modification of\nsome earlier expectations with re\ngard to its duration.\nIt is considered reassuring,\nhowever, that constructive forces\nare in operation which should\neventually effect a more definite\nturn for the better.\nOn Reserve Banks\nThe United States Treasury has\ncalled for repayment by deposi\ntory institutions in Second Fed\neral Reserve District on July 1,\nof $9,873,800, representing the\ntotal of combined amounts re\nmaining on deposit for accounts\nof certificates of indebtedness is\nsue dated March 15. This does\nnot affect deposits for the ac\ncount of issue dated June 18.\nThe call for the entire country is\n$27,486,100.\nAugust Upturn Seen\nBy Manufacturer\nCLEVELAND, June -W. R.\nMitchell, vice president, National\n\"Acme Co., maker of screws and\n\u2019dies, today said that although\nbusiness at present was at a\nrether low ebb, as was the case\nof most industries of a similar\nnature, the chances for an in\ncrease in activity in August and\nthrough the fall months seemed\nbright.\nFurther Liquidation\nOs Loans Necessary\nTo Aid Stock Strength\nBy LEWIS HANEY\nDlreetar New Yerk Oalvrreity Rnreau\n\u2022f HaelneM Research aad Farmer\nBeanomlat at Federal Trade\nCemmlaaloa.\nIn this period of liquidation, it\nis most important that anyone\nwho desires to know the facts\nshould watch developments in\nbank credit. The movement of\ncollateral loans, including\n\u201cbrokers\" loans, tells us what\nprogress is made in reducing the\nexcessive amount of credit that is\ntied up In securities.\nWe now know that last week\nthe loans to brokers were cut\n$371,000,000. That is a good sized\nreduction. It means that securi\nties held on credit were liquidated\nto about that extent \u2014say 10 per\ncent.\nSince April 30, when the spring\nhangover from the 1929 stock\nspree was at its height, the\nbrokers' loan account has been\ncut down by $858,000,000.\nBaek to 1927 Level\nBrokers* loans are now back to\nabout where they stood in the\nmiddle part of 1927. Then the\ntotal of such loans was about\n$3,100,000,000, ahd the loans made\nby others than banks were about\n$900,000,000. Now the total is\nabout $3,400,000,000 and the loans\nby \u201cothers\u201d are $939,000,000.\nPersonally, I think this is still a\nlittle high. The figures now are\nwhere they were in October, 192 7\nand even then inflation had made\nconsiderable progress.\nThe worst feature seems to be\nthe fact that as brokers\u2019 loans\nhave been reduced, the direct\nloans made by the banks on col\nlateral security have increased.\nThe total collateral loans are now\nExchange Basis Told\nIn Dry Goods Merger\nThe basis of exchange of the\nstock of Ely Walker Dry Goods\nCo., of St. Louis, for the shares\nof the recently formed United\nDry Goods Corp., a holding com\npany. were announced today.\nThree shares of Ely Walker com\nmon are to be exchanged for one\nshare of United Dry Goods pre\nferred up to one-half of the hold\nings of each stockholder. The\nremaining common will be ex\nchanged on a share for share\nbasis and a 40 per cent stock\ndividend will then be declared,\nmaking the final exchange 1 2-5\nshares of Walker for each share\nof United.\nCocoa Prices Spurt\nOn Heavy Trading\nK bull movement believed to\nhave been supported by the Brit\nish Combine, a group of cocoa\nshippers at the Gold Coast\nColony, West Africa, carried cocoa\nfutures up 48 to 58 points at the\nNew York Cocoa Exchange this\nweek. The week\u2019s trading volume\nof 882 lots, or 11,015 tons, was\nthe greatest in several months.\nLOCAL STOCKS\n(Furni\u00abh\u00bbd by W. B Hibbs A Co.)\nSALES\nCapital Traction, ss, SI,OOOO\n90%.\nCapital Traction Company, 30\n@SB; 20@58.\nNorfolk and Washington Steam\nboat, rts., wi., 3\u00a9 16%.\nPotomac Electric 5%5, pfd., 10\n@107%.\nFederal American National\nBank, 10 @275.\nMergenthaler, 10@97; 20@97;\n10097.\nReal Estate Mortgage and\nGuaranteed, pfd., 60@6%.\nAFTER CALL\nWashington Gas, 6s, A, soloo\u00a9\n101%.\nWashington Gas 6s, B, s2oo\u00a9\n103.\nWashington Rialway and Elec\ntric pfd., 20098%.\nNorfolk and Washington Steam\nboat Rts. (w| i.), 11@16%.\nPotomac Electric 6 per cent pfd.,\ns@lll.\nPeople\u2019s Drug Store pfd., 10\n103%.\nColumbia Sand and Gravel pfd.,\n20090, 10090.\nCapital Traction Company,\n5@@58%.\n_ p,bHf Boad\u00bb _l_BJd I Ask.\nArtier Tel 4 Taisa 4%s *33 102 T....\nAmer Tel 4 Tel 4%s '39.... 160 I\nAm Tel 4 Tel C\u2019tl Tr Sa.. 104%\nAnacostla 4 Pet RR is 33\nAna 4 Pot Guar Sa 94\nC 4 P Tel of Ve (a 102\nCap Traction RR is 30 91\nCity 4 Suburban 5a 01\nGeorgetown Gas Ist is 101\nPotomac Elec Cone is 102 10244\nPotomac Eled is lIOS\nWash Alex 4 Mt V Ctt....\nWash Balto 4 An is 35\nWashington Gas is ........102\nWash Gas is Series A 101% 102%\nWash Gas \u00abs Series 8..... 105 10i\nWaah Ry 4. Kl\u00bb<\\ 4a _BS 85_\ni Mlaeellaaeotas Bowds I\nBarber 4 Ross Inc 39 I 90\nChevy Chase Club 6%s 'l\u00bb0\nD C Paper Ms\u00ab Is I 50 ,70\nW M Cold Storage i 5...... I >1 1.\nWash Cons Title (1a.... 1 1100\nPwMte\" CtOity' Stocfcs i I\n\u2022Ame\"r Tel 4 Te1............\n\u2666Capitol Traction C 0...... I 17 341 59%\nWa\u00abM, ttae Lt Co |llS%|l\u2019s\nTh* National Daily\nnearly two and a half billion dol\nlars greater than in October, 1927.\nt No matter how many rallies we\nmay see in the stock market, con\nditions are not going to be right\nuntil these huge loans on securi\nties are greatly reduced. As last\nreported, they amounted to more\nthan $8,600,000,000, which is more\nthan all commercial loans.\nMost stock market cycles show\nthe same old round of credit ex\npansion and liquidation.\n1. First speculators bld money\nrates up. 2. That attracts funds\nfrom all over the world. 3. Then\nas the market gets wobbly some\nforeign funds are hastily with\ndrawn and a market crash fol\nlows. 4. The banks in New York\ncity then step in and take up the\ncredit load, increasing their loans\nto .make up for the loss of out\nside funds. 5. Finally the banks\nget their collateral loans down, as\ncontinued liquidation occurs.\nFurther Cut Necessary\nWe are now in between the\nfourth and fifth stages of this\nprocess. Outside funds are still\nbeing withdrawn, and last week\nthe biggest cut in brokers\u2019 loans\nwas due to the action of \u201cin\nterior banks\u201d outside New York.\nThe New York banks also re\nduced brokers\u2019 loans a little, but\ntheir total collateral loans are\nstill $788,000,000 larger than a\nyear ago.\nMy conclusion is that further\nliquidation is required and that\nthis means that there must be\nmore selling of securities. That\n1 will probably mean still lower\nprices for many stocks.\nRallies should be taken advan\ntage of to sell stocks that are not\nclearly worth present \u25a0'rices.\nWeek\u2019s Failures Are\nUp Over Last Year\nThe number of failures in the\nUnited States continues at a re\u2019.a\ntively high level, a total of 490\nbeing reported to R. G. Dun Co.\nthis week. Although little change\nfrom last week\u2019s 487 defaults, the\npresent number is 85 above the\n425 insolvencies of a year-ago-\nComparing with the returns for\nthe earlier year, a particularly\nlarge increase appears in the East\nwhile the South alone shows a de\n-1 crease.\nJune Crude Rubber\nConsumption Off\nConsumption of crude rubber\nby American manufacturers dur\ning the present month will total\napproximately 32.000 long tons,\nit is estimated by the Rubber\ni Exchange of New York, based\nupon operating schedules main\ntained this month at Akron and\nother producing centers. This\nwill represent a decline of about\ni 8.000 long tons from the May\ni consumption total, and 11.500\ni tons from June last year when\nconsumption reached the figure\nof 43,430 tons.\n1 Bld I Ask.\n<I*N 4 VV Mleaipboat <215 1255\nN 4 W S\u2019ttt rts wi I IS%| 16%\nPot Elec Power Ba p 81... .4110 112\nPot Elec 6%e pfd....j10<% 107%\nWaah Ry A. El c0m...... 1550\nWash Ry El pfd I 98% 99\nWash Balt A An com I 5\nWash Balt A An pfd i\nwlWhen issued. Ex rights,\nNational Bank Stocks I I\n\u2022Capital 1230 I\u2019so\n\u2022Columbia |4OO I\n\u2022Commercial (stamped) 1227 1340\n\u2022District (215 1250\n\u2022Federal-American ..1275 1300\n\u2022Liberty 1200 '220\n\u2022Lincoln .....1400 1435\nMetropolitan 1320 1305\nRiggs 1430 1470\n\u2022Second 1175 1210\n\u2022Washington |250 I\nTrust Company Stocks I I\n\u2022Amer Sec 4 Tr Co 1365 1400\nContinental Trust 1120 1140\n\u2022Merch Bk A Tr U 25 140\nNat| Saw A- Tr 1545 |530\n\u2022Union Trust 1245 |3OO\nWash Loan ,A Tr 1450 1500\nRavings Bank Stocks I I\n\u2022Bank of Bethesda ........I 69 ICi\n\u2022Com A SaV Bank |330\n\u2022East Washington I 20 I 35\nPot Ravings Bank I 60 I 65\n\u2022Sec Sav A Con Bank |471 1500\n\u2022Seventh Street 1310 I\n\u2022United States |530 I\nWash Mechanics.. I 50 I\nFire Insurance Stocks I\nAmerican ..I3li I\nCorcoran 150 I\n\u2022Firemen\u2019s I 3*%l 4 0\nNational Union I 23 I 26\nTitle Insurance Stocks I\nColumbia j 8%l 12\nReal Estate |l5O 1..,.\nTitle A Inv Co Md c0m.... I 20 130\nMiseertaneotis stocks t\nBarber A Ro\u00abs Inc c0m....1 15%1 20\nChew Ch Dairy pfd 1103 'lO9\n\u2022Col Sand A Grav pfd.... I 90 I 94\nD C Paper Mfg pfd I 15 I 50\n\u2022Dist Natl Sec pfd I 67 80\n\u2022Enter Bromo-Selx I 30 I 33\n\u2022Federal Storage pfd ..1110 1125\n\u2022Fed-Am Co com 199 1101\nLanston Monotype 1114%|115%\n\u2022Mer Tr Stge com ..|102%|10\u00ab\n\u2022Met Tr Stge PM ..I, \u00bb7 1100\n\u2022Mergenthaler Lino I 9\u00ab%| 97%\n\u2022Nat) Mtge A Inv pfd I 4%; 5%\nPeople Drug S pfd 1103%110i\n\u2022Real Est MAC pfd I 0%l\nSecurity Storage IH4 'lit\n\u2022Ter Ref A Wh Corp I 47%| 52\n\u2022The Carpel Coi ji I 21 I 25\nW Meeh Mtge com I 9 %l 10\n\u2022Wash Med Bldg C0rp....1 92 1...\u2019..\n\u2022Wdwd 4 Lothrop pfd 1105 Hi\u2019\nPrince George* Bk 4 Tr. .1 30 I 40\n\u00bbEx Dividend. dEx-rlghta t 3 per\nextra.\nMONDAY, JUNE 80, lt3b\nI*\u25a0 I 11l 111\nStartles\nI .1 I ...I\u2014 ,1 \u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u2014l\n\u25a0MM\nli. z .t*\nA\ni a w\u00dfnr\n\u2014Tlmea Staff Pl\u00bbto*\nHENRY FORD\nDETROIT automobile mag\nnate, whose adoption of Amer\nlean methods in his European\nfactories have threatened an in\ndustrial revolution. Under the\nFord plan workers are paid\ndouble and even triple the\nsalaries received by those in\nadjoining factories.\nEMPWIHT\nACTION GAINS\nExperiments in stabilizing em\nployment through management\ncontrol promise a solution to one\nof the most vexing of modem\neconomic problems. according to\nThe Index, publsihed by the\nNew York Trust Company.\n\u201cEven a temporary curtail\nment of aggregate wages may.\naffect the economic status of\nthe country to an important\ndegree,\u201d the review states. \u201cThe\nAmerican Federation of Labor\nestimates that the United\nStates lost $1,000,009,000 of buy\ning power through unemploy\nment during the first quarter\nof 1930. The Bureau of Labor\nStatistics figures that the fluc\ntuation in volume of employ\nment in the manufacturing in\ndustries spells usually intermit\ntent unemployment for the\n9,000,000 persons engaged in\nthose industries, to an extent\nequivalent to a full year's idle\nness of 1,509,000 to 1,790,000\npersons.\u201d a\nWhile the Government is. en\ndeavoring to relieve unemploy\nment through Federal building\nprograms and the collection of\nstatistics, industry has adopted\nmeasures on its own accoun-c to\nbalance labor needs through more\nefficient planning of operations.\nOne of the bases of reform has\nbeen a closer adjustment of pro\nduction to market demand. Prob\nable sales are estimated a year\nin advance, and output is distrib\nuted evenly over the 12-morith\nperiod. Manufacture to stock is\nmade possible through standard\nization of product and adequate\nstorage facilities, and the excess\nproduction in one period is. stored,\nagainst an anticipated increase\nin demand.\nAnother method for regulariz\ning plant operation is diversifica\ntion of output. Periodic reces\nsions have likewise been reduced\nby encouraging off-season pur\nchases through intensive adver\ntising, lower prices or special con\ncessions, outside the manufac\nturing industries, the five-day\nweek has helped of employment\nin building trades.\nPennsy Completes\nWest Jersey Lease\nGeneral W. W. Atterbury, presi\ndent of the Pennsylvania railroad, _\nannounced today the lease of the\nWest Jersey and Seashore Rail\nroad to the Pnnsylvania for 999\nyeart having been approved by\nthe directors and stockholders Os\nboth companies and the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission, will\nbecome effective July 1. The West\nJersey and Seashore today de-,\ndared a special 5 per cent divi\ndend upon the common stock,\npayable July 15 to holders of rec\nord June 30.\nThis is a special dividend to\nadjust the situation to July L\nwhen the lease becomes effective.\nUnder the lease terms, dividends\nwill be paid at the rate of 6 per\ncent per annum, semi-annually on I\nthe first business day of January\nand July.\nW. B. HIBBS CO.\nThe ONLY New York Stock Exchange House\nHaving, Its Main Office in Washington\n\u2014\u2014MEMBERS\nNew York Stock Exchange\nBoston Stock Exchange\nPhiladelphia, Stock Exchange\nWashington Stock Exchange\nNew York Cotton Exchange\nChicago Board of Trade,\nAmerican Bankers Aseociation\nDistrict Bankers Association\n\nHIBBS BUILDING\nNational 0540 WASHINGTON, D. C.\nWHEATPOSITION\nHAS LITTLE TO\nGOMHIL\nLowest Prices Reached Last\nWeelf in Sixteen Years;\nExperts Frankly Worried\nBy SAUL LEHRER\nWheat prices this week sank to\nthe lowest levels in 16 years.\nWith the grain at this figure\nthe farmer receives about 70 cents\na bushel for- his product to re\npay him for his labor and other\nexpenses involved ih raising it, x\nThe weakness ih the wheat\nmarked is due to a 'surplus of thte\ncommodity all over the world. A\nlarge carry over from last year\u2019s\ncrop aggravates the situation.\nThe decline has been helped\nalong by a sharply falling stock\nmarket. But with the season ad\nvancing to a point where harvest\ning will soon begin, traders will\ndivorce the stock market from\ntheir calculations and devote\ntheir attention to such factors as\nI deal solely with wheat.\nMore Wheat Coming\nThe most important fact with\nwhich the grain market has to\ncontend witft is wheat\nis there. There is too much al\nready. Fith more coming. Can\nada has steadily increased ,her\nwheat-growing area by means of\nthe Marquis wheat. This type of\ngtaln by virtue of its quick grow\ning quality, has enabled the Do\nminion to expand its grain rais\ning activities into the Northwest,\nan area heretofore unsuited to\nthis product.\nRussia, after several years of\ninactivity, has again come back\nas a premier producer and is\nexporting her surplus into Eu\nropean markets. Australia .has\nincreased her production in ex\ncess of 91 per cent through the\nuse of Federation wheat, a type\nsimilar to that raited in Canada.\nThe Argentine since 1913 has\nraised her production 32 per cent,\nthereby adding to a commodity\nwith which the world is already\nglutted.\nLess Wheat Consumed\nThe whys and wherefores of\noverproduction are interesting as\nthey bring ihto view factors which\nseem unimportant when observed\ncasually. With the situation as\nbad as it is today, however, every\ndetail must be viewed to see\nwhether or not it can be turned\ntoward the solution of the prob\nlem. To some extent the situa\ntion is caused not only because\nmore wheat is being grown but\nthat less is being consumed.\nThe displacement of the horse\nand the mule on the farm and m\nthe city by the tractor and tl!e\nautomobile has deprived the\nfarmer of an outlet nevertheless.\nThe propaganda in favor of vege\ntables and vitamins and the diet\nfads are among the reasons for\nthe 15 per cent decline in the\nconsumption of bread in the\nUnited States alone.\nFurthermore as the monthly\npublication of the Central Bank\nof Chile point out. \u201cThe rational\nization of industry and the in\ncreasing mechanization through\nout the world mean the gradual\ndisappearance of heavy labor.\nThe workman is becoming a ma\nchine minder. Consequently the\namount of food necesary for\neach workman is diminishing.\u201d\nDepression a Factor\nThe depression of prices now\ncurrent throughout the world\nmust not be lost sight of. When\nmen are unemployed and wages\nare reduced there is always an\naccompanying drop in the amount\nand quality of the food eaten.\nThe fall in price of silver has\nseriously reduced the ability of\npeople in China, Mexico find In\ndia to. buy the bare necessities of\nHfe.\nWorkers Kept Busy\nIn Rural Northwest\nMINNEAPOLIS. June S\nFairly heavy rains during the\nweek have improved the crop\noutlook, especially in the spring\nwheat sections, but the likeli\nhood of a large wheat crop is\ncomplicating the terminal stdr-\nI age situation in the face of 10,-\n000,000 bushels shortage in ele\nvator space.\nI IJEIRI\nOIL INDUSTRY\nSEEN IN GOOD\nPOSITION\nE. B. Reeser, of Petroleum\nBoard, Outlines Good Future\nUnder Conservative Program\nThe oil industry generally is In\na good position. E. B, Reeser,\nAmerican Petroleum Institute\npresident, said in a statement;\nreleased today..\nProduction of crude oil. is run\nning about 300,000 barrels daily\nbehind the output of a year ago\nand domestic consumption and.\nexports are about 100,000 barrels\ngreater, he pointed out;\nWhile local conditions in some\nsections may force certain price\nreadjustments, he said, there was\nno indication of a generally weak\nened price structure in, the mid\ncontinent territory.\nPreduction In Hand\nCurtailment of production along\nthe lines approved by the Fed\neral Oil Conservation Board, he\nclaimed, has kept the crude Oil'\nsituation well in hand and it will\nremain so far the balance of the\nyear. The curtailment program\nis getting 100 per cent co-opera\ntion in Oklahoma, Kansas and\nCalifornia. r\nRefiners have not. curtailed op\nerations sufficiently, Reeser said.,\nagreements in that division being\nhampered by interstate commerce\ndifficulties.\nOn curent crude oil price levels,\nMr. Reeser expressed the opinion\nthat they were not profitable for\nany but flush fields. He added\nthat with continued co-operation\nin cutting supplies to fit demand,\nthere was every reasonable ex\npectation of firmer price levels.\nRefiners\u2019 Stocks\n'\u2018With regard to the refining\nsection of the industry,*' he said,\n\"it must be noted that the in\nstitute did not organise a- refin\ning section until December, 1929.\nAs it took about two years of un\nremitting effort to obtain results\nin the institute\u2019s crude curtail-\nment program, we must not ex\npect immediate results in the' re-.\nfining department of the in-,\ndustry.\n\"We have been given definite\nindication, however, that the re\nfiners are alive to the advisability\nof adjusting their operations so\nas to produce only the quantities\nof products required to fill\nactual demand. It is encourag\ning to note that in June to date\nrefiners\u2019 stocks of gasoline show\na reduction of approximately\n2.5M.000 barrels, a greater rate\nof decrease than in any like\nperiod.\n\"Speaking generally on the oil\nindustry, I believe it to be in an\nunusually good, position.\"\nU. S. Firm Will Make\nTires in Argentine\nARKON. 0.. June 59 (1N5.,)\u2014\nConstruction of a tire factory at\nBuenos Aires. Argentine, by the\nFirestone Tire and Rubber Com-\npany. will be started Tuesday, ac-\ncording to an announcement of\ncompany officials..\nLife\nIsn\u2019t K\nComplete\nunless you\nknow\" the joys of\nowning a home\nof your own;\nmany opportuni-\nties are offered\nthrough the Keal\nEstate so r Sale\ncolumns of to\nday\u2019s\u2014\nTimes Classified 